      				<div class='pad'>

	        				        			
	        				        			
	        				        				<h1 class="title">
	        					Friday, June 13, 2008 - A Walk Around the Farm	        				</h1>
	        				        			
	        				        			
	        				        			
	        				        			
	        				        			
	        			<div id="node-137" class="node ntype-blog">

  
  
      <span class="submitted">Tue, 2008-06-17 10:40 — VFC</span>
  
  <div class="meta">
      </div>

  <div class="content">
    <p>The days blend together into slow sameness. Up early. A cup of coffee. Straightening up around the house. Washing clothes by hand and hanging them to dry. Chatting. The kids playing with each other. Even reading without me asking them!<br /><br />In the afternoon, we walk with Abilio down the road past the small school where Bertilia teaches 90 students in six grades by herself (the other teachers that the school officials send keep leaving!) Then past the empty unfinished visitor center - a monument to poor planning and corruption. Built a few years ago to welcome visitors to the National Park of Comayagua, a protected area of the mountains just above the family´s farm. Money was obtained through an international grant and the building was started but never finished and now it sits empty.</p><p>Nearby a number of young men from the community are playing soccer in an open field set aside for that purpose. We go out into the steep pasture where Guillermo´s Dad let his cows graze and admire the incredible view of the valley and the waterway with its path of trees below. Then we take a path through a small woods that Abilio refers to fondly as his &quot;refuge&quot;. Only about 10 years old (I have pictures of it when it was a bare field recently planted to beans), it is now full of a wild diversity of tall trees, banana plants, bamboo and more.<br /><br />The path leads to Abilio and Bertilia´s property. We see the beans Abilio is growing. And his two fish ponds. And then check out the three cabins (&quot;eco-casitas&quot;) that they rent out to tourists. Rustic but comfortable. Complete with small porches in front, furniture Abilio has made out of tree that have fallen down over the years, and a great view of the forest. They can currently hold 4 people in each cabin and have hosted groups of more than 20 over the years. Abilio and Bertilia are excited about the potential for eco-tourism in this beautiful place.</p>  </div>
  
      <div class="links"><ul class="links inline"><li class="blog_usernames_blog first"><a href="../blog/4" title="Read VFC&#039;s latest blog entries.">VFC&#039;s blog</a></li>
